\begin_layout Standard
The medical use of silver, both as a Ag(0) and as compounds of Ag(I) is
 known since millennia, the ancient Persians, Phoenicians, Greeks, Romans
 and others were recorded to utilize various forms of silver to preserve
 both food and water, the custom practiced through World War II.
 The first preserved records of medical use of silver comes from Macedonians,
 who have attempted to treat infections with silver plates.
 Hippocrates, the Father of Medicine, was supposed to use silver preparations
 to treat the ulcers and promote wound healing.
 Before the introduction of antibiotics, silver, and various silver compounds
 were the most available antimicrobial agents.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "AlexanderWesley2009"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 The toxicity of silver is low compared to most of other heavy metals, which
 allows the use of silver in various utility goods, e.
 g.
 jewellery, silverware, or as a food additive.
 However it has been shown that high doses of silver given parenternally,
 can cause convulsions or even death.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "AlexanderWesley2009"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 Though the silver toxicity is low, the organisms usually lack the mechanisms
 for silver detoxification, and in case of human body, when silver is delivered
 (e.g., injection, ingestion or applied topically) silver is accumulated irreversi
bly.
 The condition caused by sustained silver exposure (and light
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Like in a photography sunlight causes the decomposition of colorless silver
 compounds to Ag(0) or silver sulfides.
\end_layout

\end_inset

) is called argyria.
 By 1939 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "Hill1939"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 have identified 357 cases of recorded argyria, all of the recorded cases,
 except from the irreversible bluish skin tone, had benign course of the
 disease.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hill1939"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 Despite low toxicity, the number of publications dedicated to silver toxicity
 by the year increases (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ag_hg_count"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), possibly the reason for this is the use of silver in everyday articles
 (e.g., use of the silver in deodorants, sportswear, anti-smoking pills),
 of which a lot of these items utilize 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
glspl{agnp}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

